						               													<description>Winner of the UK GAMES EXPO Award for BEST ABSTRACT GAME 2017&amp;#10;&amp;#10;1864, Ominus Valley, Egypt &amp;mdash; a hoard of 6,000-year-old game cubes is found. No one knows how to play this mysterious game &amp;mdash; until now when this ancient game is reborn as Ominoes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In this abstract strategy/tactical game, 2-4 players want to collect their favored gods &amp;mdash; Horus, Ra, Apep, and Khepri &amp;mdash; in groups to earn points. They do this by rolling custom dice that both determine actions and are placed on the game board to count as a piece of the player's color. On a turn, the active player does the following:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;    Roll: Take a die and roll it.&amp;#10;    Move: Move a die on the board that matches the rolled color exactly three spaces.&amp;#10;    Place: Placing the die just rolled on the board, possibly scoring a group.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The dice have four faces matching the players colors, with unused colors in a two- or three-player game being scorable by anyone. The other two faces &amp;mdash; &amp;quot;Yay-Ra&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;Ominotep&amp;quot; &amp;mdash; allow the player to move or reroll any die, respectively, and they count as wild once on the board. Groups of four (or more) dice of a color are scored immediately and give their player points equal to their number. The first player to 13 points (or 21 points in a two-player game)wins!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Quick to learn, easy to play but with layers of light tactics. Ominoes is 15 minutes of play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
